Donald Trump‚Äôs First Wife Was Under FBI Counterintelligence Investigation: Report
Ivana Trump, the first wife of former President Donald Trump, was under FBI counterintelligence investigation after she eventually ended up in the U.S. after migrating out of then-communist Czechoslovakia.
Bloomberg News obtained scores of pages from an FBI file on Ivana Trump that included their findings from the international investigation that spanned from Europe to Canada.
The ‚Äúsecret‚Äù files said that in 1989 the FBI recommended opening an investigation into Ivana Trump based on information that bureau received from a confidential source. The FBI report noted that the allegations could have stemmed from ‚Äújealousies of her wealth and fame.‚Äù
Much is still not known about the two-year investigation other than it involved the FBI‚Äôs counterintelligence division and was deemed ‚Äúhighly sensitive.‚Äù
The FBI file reportedly had little information about Donald Trump in it.
The report said that the FBI found 900 pages of material that it had on Ivana Trump and, after being sued by Bloomberg News, agreed to release nearly 200 pages this week and will release the remainder next month.
The bureau can release the information now since Ivana Trump is no longer alive.
Donald Trump announced Ivana‚Äôs passing last July in a statement he posted to social media.
‚ÄúI am very saddened to inform all of those that loved her, of which there are many, that Ivana Trump has passed away at her home in New York City,‚Äù the former president said in a statement. ‚ÄúShe was a wonderful, beautiful, and amazing woman, who led a great and inspirational life. Her pride and joy were her three children, Donald Jr., Ivanka, and Eric. She was so proud of them, as we were all so proud of her. Rest In Peace, Ivana!‚Äù
Ivana Trump was mother to the three oldest Trump children, Donald Trump Jr., Ivanka Trump, and Eric Trump.
Ivana Marie Zeln√≠ckov√° was born under communist rule in the former Czechoslovakia. She was athletically gifted growing up as she participated in competitive skiing starting at the age of six and continued skiing through college and reportedly was an alternate for the country‚Äôs Olympic team in the 1972.
Ivana Trump later immigrated to Canada in the 1970s where she worked as a ski instructor before starting her modeling career which landed her in New York in 1976 ‚Äî where she quickly met Donald Trump.
Ivana Trump married Donald Trump in 1977. The couple later got divorced in 1992.
The New York Times reported that Ivana Trump was a ‚Äúcritical part‚Äù in Donald Trump building his real-estate business, describing her as extremely hard working and with a keen eye for details. At one point she served as vice president for interior design at the Trump Organization.
Ivana Trump and Donald Trump were on good terms in recent years, reportedly speaking as often as once a week, as she supported him politically and encouraged his use of Twitter.
Ivana Trump was married to Alfred Winklmayr before she met Donald Trump. Ivana Trump‚Äôs marriage to Winklmayr lasted two years.
After her marriage to Trump, Ivana Trump married Riccardo Mazzucchelli in 1995. That marriage later ended in 1997.

0n this day in 1982 in his 21st year of coaching and coaching in his 7th Final Four, on a jumper by a skinny freshman named Michael Jordan, Dean Smith finally wins his first College Basketball National Championship. I was 11 years old when he arrived at UNC and 47 when he retired.

March 29th

1982:
There is a little over a minute left in the game. The University of North Carolina is playing Georgetown for the National Championship. This is North Carolina's Coach Dean Smith's seventh trip to the Final Four without bringing home the trophy, and Carolina is losing, again. Georgetown's Eric ‚ÄúSleepy‚Äù Floyd (ironically from Gaston, North Carolina) has just put the Hoya's up 62-61.

Dean calls timeout. Gathering the team around him, he gambles that Georgetown will be looking for the ball to go to UNC's high scorers, James Worthy or Sam Perkins. So Smith draws up a play that puts the ball in the hands of his young freshman, Michael Jordan. He looks Jordan in the eyes and tells him not to be afraid to shoot if the ball finds him.

As play begins again, Carolina's point guard Jimmy Black sees Jordan open on the left wing and whips him the ball. And with 12 seconds left, ON THIS DAY, Michael Jordan calmly sinks what will prove to be the game-winning shot.

However, there are still twelve seconds to play, and a lot happens in that last twelve seconds. Receiving the ball on the inbound, Georgetown's Fred Brown gets the ball over the half-court line only to mistakenly fire a pass to Carolina's James Worthy. Worthy turns and races with the ball for the Carolina basket. He is fouled with 3 seconds left, and proving he knows a good anti-climax when he sees one...promptly misses both of them. No matter, time runs out on the Hoya's and, finally, it's Carolina. Dean Smith has his National Championship.



-Michael Jordan hits the game-winning shot that gives North Carolina their first National Championship of the Dean Smith era.

Woody Durham's play by play: "THE TAR HEELS ARE GOING TO WIN THE NATIONAL CHAMPIONSHIP!!!") as the final seconds tick off. And shortly he'll be on Franklin Street with a hundred-thousand other deliriously joyful Carolina hearts.

-The 1982 North Carolina Tar Heels.

-The Tar Heels starting five: clockwise from Dean, Jimmy Black, Michael Jordan, Sam Perkins, Matt Doherty, James Worthy.

With flags ordered to be flown at half mast on every federal building in the country, hardly anyone has missed the shooting in Nashville on Monday. The media covered it like a blanket. Wikipedia has 33 sources informing its coverage. This writer read 17 more as background for this article.

Only one thing is missing: Not a single source dared even to ask the question, why? Why did this 28-year-old person, born a female but later deciding she was a male ‚Äî tossing her given name for a male descriptor instead ‚Äî draw up maps for several potential targets, legally purchase at least of the two of the three firearms she carried into The Covenant School on Monday, and, in the space of 14 minutes, manage to murder three children and three adults, including the school‚Äôs administrator?

Why, indeed?

The police did what they could. She entered the school at 10:13 a.m. and was shot dead at 10:27 a.m. There were five officers who approached the building, dodging fire from the shooter on their way in. Two of them cornered her on the second floor and shot her dead.

Police spokesmen said it could have been worse.

How much worse? There were more than 200 children in school on Monday, along with about 50 teachers and staff. The shooter picked the school over others she had considered because it was the least protected: There was no safety officer ‚Äî School Resource Officer, or SRO ‚Äî present. She had attended the school years earlier and knew her way around. She planned the attack in advance, drawing maps of the facility with possible entrances carefully noted.

She left a manifesto, which police are reviewing.

People are grieving, including the family of the senior pastor of the church that sponsors the school who lost his daughter in the shooting.

President Biden is calling for more gun control even though the shooter obtained her firearms legally. His press secretary blamed the incident on Republicans. The Gun Violence Archive reported that in 2022 there were 646 mass shootings (by their count), with 314 children killed and 681 adults killed by gunfire.

Moms Demand Action seized the opportunity to blame the guns and the few lawmakers who still think the Second Amendment counts for something:

School shootings are not acts of nature ‚Äî they‚Äôre manmade acts of cowardice enabled by lawmakers who have accepted children being shot in their school as an acceptable price to pay for the support of the gun industry.

In America and in Tennessee, guns are the leading killer of kids yet Tennessee lawmakers have done nothing but gut gun safety laws, putting gun industry profits ahead of the safety of our children. We don‚Äôt have to live this way and our children certainly don‚Äôt have to die this way.

So said Shannon Watts, the MDA founder.

Journalist Andy Ngo thinks it might have had something to do with Tennessee having recently passed laws prohibiting the ‚Äúmedical transitioning‚Äù of minors in the state.

Nashville District Attorney Glenn Funk said, ‚ÄúThis is the ultimate crime.‚Äù

No. With all respect due to the attorney general, the shooting on Monday at The Covenant School in Nashville, Tennessee, is not the ultimate crime. The ultimate crime is not asking the question, why?

Eric Metaxas comes close to the answer, and it has to do with the Presbyterian Church of America, with which The Covenant School is associated, along with many other major so-called Christian denominations. Wrote Metaxas in his ‚ÄúLetter to the American Church‚Äù:

The ideas and forces we face have an atheistic Marxist ideology in common.‚Ä¶ [They] share a bitter taproot that leads all the way down to Hell.

Critical Race Theory ‚Äî which is atheistic and Marxist ‚Äî and radical transgender and pro-abortion ideologies are all inescapably anti-God and anti-human.

They are decidedly at war with the ideas of family and marriage, and with the idea of America as a force for good‚Ä¶.

These ideas have over many decades infiltrated our own culture in such a way that they touch everything.

Where is the church? Where are the pastors loudly declaiming against this infiltration? For the most part they are silent, as is the kept media.

Put simply, what would one expect from a generation that has been brainwashed into thinking that there is no God, that life is meaningless and purposeless, that humans evolved from slime and mud. Why wouldn‚Äôt they shoot each other? There‚Äôs no conscience, no morality, no right and wrong. In today‚Äôs culture, even to ask about morality and conscience is to be labeled a fanatic, or worse.

That‚Äôs why the question ‚Äúwhy?‚Äù is never raised. It‚Äôs much easier for those behind the destructive ideologies being taught in schools to blame guns and gun owners. It avoids the real question.

Does ‚ÄúThe Law‚Äù Exist?
Legal Moderns Send the Law Packing

by Thomas E. Lordan

...Think of the very beginning of the Psalms 1: ‚ÄúBlessed is the man who walks not in the counsel of the wicked, nor stands in the way of sinners, nor sits in the seat of scoffers; but his delight is in the law of the Lord, and on his law he meditates day and night.‚Äù At least a faint sense of this may still be preserved even in our secular society when its members refer to ‚Äúthe law,‚Äù though without being able to penetrate to the heart of the mystery they have thereby invoked.

Various cognate terms have been used from time immemorial to express essentially what is meant by ‚Äúthe law‚Äù.... They include such terms as ‚Äúthe natural law‚Äù or ‚Äúthe higher law,‚Äù which suggest the relationship of law to its ultimate origin in the divine.

C. S. Lewis used the ancient Chinese term the Tao, ‚Äúfor brevity,‚Äù to refer to a

"conception in all its forms, Platonic, Aristotelian, Stoic, Christian, and Oriental alike, [have in common] something we cannot neglect. It is the doctrine of objective value, the belief that certain attitudes are really true, and others really false, to the kind of thing the universe is and the kind of things we are. . . . [It] is not one among a series of possible systems of value. It is the sole source of all value judgements. If it is rejected, all value is rejected. If any value is retained, it is retained.

It is only in the last couple of hundred years or so that legal philosophy has called the existence of ‚Äúthe law‚Äù into serious doubt, and this has occurred, not coincidentally, concurrently with modernity‚Äôs doubts about the existence of God....

... Even those who toil in the fields of law, judges and lawyers, refer not just to ‚Äúlaws‚Äù or ‚Äúa law,‚Äù but to ‚Äúthe law‚Äù as if it is something really existent, something objective, something in some sense ‚Äúabove and beyond‚Äù individual positive laws, something they cannot create but which they must strive to discover as a norm...

In the practice of law, how often we hear disappointed lawyers and the litigants they represent bemoan the fact that a judge got ‚Äúthe law‚Äù completely wrong in their case. Of such disappointments appeals are made...

And in speaking of appeals to higher courts, the mystery grows. A court of appeals will often reverse the trial court, finding that the lower court got ‚Äúthe law‚Äù wrong, while a supreme court may then reverse the court of appeals for the same reason. Different judges on these higher courts may disagree among themselves in the same case. Dissents are common.

Even the U.S. Supreme Court may find that it got ‚Äúthe law‚Äù wrong years after it rendered a decision purporting to tell us what ‚Äúthe law‚Äù was. Think of Brown v. Board of Education, the 1954 decision in which the Court required the racial integration of public schools, thereby overruling its 1896 decision in Plessy v. Ferguson, which had found separate public facilities for whites and blacks to be ‚Äúequal.‚Äù

Or think of Dobbs v. Jackson Women‚Äôs Health Organization, the relatively recent case in which the Court overruled its 1973 decision in Roe v. Wade and its 1992 decision in Planned Parenthood v. Casey regarding abortion. Can these reversals be attributed merely to different interpretations of our positive, written laws, or is there something else at play, some force called ‚Äúthe law‚Äù which somehow compels jurists to reevaluate their work?

By ‚Äúthe law‚Äù we appear to mean something normative. The term seems to be a shorthand way of introducing a moral sense into law. ‚ÄúThe law‚Äù suggests what the laws ought to be. It provides a standard or measure for laws. It is aspirational. While there is a distinction to be drawn between law and morals, a society generally strives to embody its sense of right and wrong in its positive laws, the laws that get written down, but it never fully succeeds in doing so, because no human work is perfect. There is a tension, which may rise to the level of personal or social consciousness, between ‚Äúthe law‚Äù and at least certain positive laws, between the ‚Äúlaw‚Äù that is and ‚Äúthe law‚Äù that ought to be.

The effort to conform positive laws to ‚Äúthe law‚Äù is fundamental for the sake not only of genuine political order but also of personal order, because the positive laws of any society are among its greatest moral teachers.

Think of what America was taught about the dignity of all Americans by Plessy v. Ferguson, or about the value of all human life by Roe and Casey. A society that refuses to see any relationship between law and morality becomes decadent. ‚ÄúThe understanding of just order,‚Äù said the German-American political philosopher Eric Voegelin, ‚Äúprogresses concretely through the reaction of a soul sensitive to the transcendent source of order against injustice in the environment.‚Äù
